The initiatives that emerge may well have his name on them, but they will not be his in any real sense. And that’s good.
The wider lesson for the rest of us? As followers, stop worshipping personalities and start looking for competent teams to back. There are no human messiahs and saviours — not unless they know how to get things done through others.
Behind the scenes
To any budding leader out there, I would say this: your primary role is to create the conditions in which good things can be done — by others. It is not to be the busiest person in the organisation; it is not to be present in every meeting; it is not to be smiling at every camera.
For much of the time, you should be invisible, working behind the scenes to develop your team’s kinship and camaraderie, and to use your authority to make their work easier.
That is the actual essence of leadership — to nurture and to enable. The end result should be a hive mind and a collective spirit that can rise to enormous challenges.
Working behind the scenes should not be mistaken for weakness. True strength is not loud and attention-seeking; it is calm and reflective and it comes up with long-term solutions, not just hysterical knee-jerk responses.



